cyclone.name: ETA
cyclone.current_location: about 140 mi WSW of the Dry Tortugas and 125 mi N of the western tip of Cuba
cyclone.trajectory: Eta is forecast to slow, then turn northward mid-week and track toward the eastern Gulf of Mexico, approaching the west-central Florida coast before curving northeast across the northern peninsula.
cyclone.expected_landfall_location: north-central Gulf coast of the Florida peninsula (Big Bend/Cedar Key vicinity)

weather_observation.watch_coast: None in effect for Florida as of Advisory 38
weather_observation.warning_coast: None in effect for Florida as of Advisory 38
weather_observation.impacted_coast: Entire west coast of Florida from the Keys northward to the Big Bend region is inside the 5-day cone
weather_observation.rain_fall_above_4_inch: Possible (2-5 inches forecast, isolated higher totals cannot be ruled out)
weather_observation.storm_surge_above_3_feet: Possible (2-4 ft surge is plausible in Tampa Bay with onshore flow)
weather_observation.wind: Tropical-storm-force winds (35–45 mph gusting 50 mph) possible late Wednesday into Thursday
weather_observation.storm_surge: Minor to moderate coastal flooding of 2–4 ft above ground level along Tampa Bay and adjacent coastline during peak onshore winds/tides
weather_observation.rainfall: Heavy rain bands could produce 2–5 inches with localized higher amounts, leading to urban and low-lying area flooding
weather_observation.other_hazards: High surf and dangerous rip currents; brief tornadoes in outer rainbands cannot be ruled out
